## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no equivalent exists
3. The idiomatic replacement is `CancellationToken` + `Task` with cooperative cancellation

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async-first overload (preferred)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Non-cooperative work** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative* — the `work` delegate **must** check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to I/O APIs. Ignoring the token means the work runs to completion despite the timeout. |
| **`Task.Run` uses ThreadPool** | The old code created a dedicated thread. CPU-bound work that blocks a pool thread can cause ThreadPool starvation. For long-blocking work, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |
| **Fire-and-forget leaks** | `WaitAsync` / `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` may return on timeout while the background task is *still running*. The old `Abort()` forcibly killed it. You must design work to honor cancellation or accept the leaked task. |
| **Exception wrapping** | The original threw `AggregateException`. `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps to the inner exception directly. Update callers that `catch (AggregateException)`. |
| **Deadlock risk** | `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` on the sync overload can deadlock in UI/ASP.NET contexts with a `SynchronizationContext`. Prefer the async overload. |

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// The work must cooperate with cancellation:
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct); // token passed through
    return ComputeResult(ct);
}, timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If You Can't Modify the Work Delegate

For legacy code where `Func<T>` doesn't accept a token (truly non-cooperative), you can abandon the task on timeout — but **the work keeps running** in the background:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

    // ⚠️ Task is still running — no way to force-kill it
    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

This is the closest behavioral match but trades the old "hard abort" for a resource leak. There is **no safe equivalent** to `Thread.Abort()` in .NET 8 — cooperative cancellation is the only supported pattern.
